[{"id":"VH904653","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a circuit diagram. A battery is connected in series with an open switch, a resistor R, and two parallel configurations. In the first parallel configuration, capacitor C sub 1 is connected in parallel with voltmeter V sub 1. In the second parallel configuration, capacitor C sub 2 is connected in parallel with voltmeter V sub 2.\" height=\"208\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH904653.g08.png\" width=\"215\" /></div>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a scatterplot with a trend line in a coordinate plane. A series of points and a trend line are indicated on the graph. The horizontal axis is labeled Voltage V sub 1, in volts, and the numbers 0 through 8, in increments of 2, are indicated. The vertical axis is labeled Voltage V sub 2, in volts, and the numbers 0 through 14, in increments of 2, are indicated. The trend line begins at the origin, and slants upwards and to the right to end at the point 6 volts, comma 12 volts. Each point lies along the trend line, beginning at the origin and moving upwards and to the right, getting closer to the end point 6 volts, comma 12 volts at a decreasing rate, creating a cluster of points.\" height=\"219\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH904653.g05.png\" width=\"340\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Two capacitors, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C sub 1\"><math alttext=\"C sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C sub 2\"><math alttext=\"C sub 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, are initially uncharged and are connected with a resistor, switch, and battery as shown in the circuit above. Voltmeters are used to collect data for the potential difference <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"V sub 1\"><math alttext=\"V sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> across capacitor <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C sub 1\"><math alttext=\"C sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and potential difference <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"V sub 2\"><math alttext=\"V sub 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> across capacitor <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C sub 2\"><math alttext=\"C sub 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> at regular intervals of time after the switch is closed. The data are plotted in the graph shown. Which of the following claims supports the results of the experiment?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH904653_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The capacitors are in series, so the amount of charge stored on each capacitor is always the same, and therefore the magnitude of the slope shows that capacitor <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C sub 2\"><math alttext=\"C sub 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> has twice the capacitance as capacitor <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C sub 1\"><math alttext=\"C sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The capacitors are in series, so the amount of charge stored on each capacitor is always the same, and therefore the magnitude of the slope shows that capacitor <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C sub 2\"><math alttext=\"C sub 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> has half the capacitance as capacitor <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C sub 1\"><math alttext=\"C sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The capacitors are in series, so the current for each capacitor is always the same, and therefore the magnitude of the slope shows that capacitor <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C sub 2\"><math alttext=\"C sub 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> has twice the resistance as capacitor <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C sub 1\"><math alttext=\"C sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The capacitors are in parallel, so the current for capacitor <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C sub 1\"><math alttext=\"C sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> is inversely proportional to the current for capacitor <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C sub 2\"><math alttext=\"C sub 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, and therefore the magnitude of the slope shows that capacitor <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C sub 2\"><math alttext=\"C sub 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> has half the resistance as capacitor <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C sub 1\"><math alttext=\"C sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The linear graph indicates that one or both capacitors are not working correctly. The potential difference across the capacitors should produce an exponential curve, not a straight-line graph.</p>"],"answer":1}]